To solve this, we first condense the equations using the properties of logarithms.
\begin{align*} \log_{10} \left( x \cdot \gcd(x,y)^2 \right) &= \log_{10} (10^{60})\\ \log_{10} \left( y \cdot \text{lcm}(x,y)^2 \right) &= \log_{10} (10^{570}) \end{align*}
or equivalently,
\begin{align*} x\gcd(x,y)^2 &= 10^{60}\\ y\text{lcm}(x,y)^2 &= 10^{570}. \end{align*}
We know that $\gcd(x,y) \cdot \text{lcm}(x,y) = xy$, and thus $x\text{lcm}(x,y) = xy$ and $y\text{lcm}(x,y) = xy$.
Let $a$ be the exponent of $10$ in the prime factorization of $x$ and $b$ be the exponent of $10$ in the prime factorization of $y$. Then,
\begin{align*} x &= 2^a\cdot5^a\\ y &= 2^b\cdot5^b \end{align*}
and
\begin{align*} \gcd(x,y) &= 2^{\min(a,b)}\cdot5^{\min(a,b)}\\ \text{lcm}(x,y) &= 2^{\max(a,b)}\cdot5^{\max(a,b)}. \end{align*}
From the equations,
\begin{align*} 2^{a+2\min(a,b)}\cdot5^{a+2\min(a,b)} &= 10^{60} = 2^{60}\cdot5^{60}\\ 2^{b+2\max(a,b)}\cdot5^{b+2\max(a,b)} &= 10^{570} = 2^{570}\cdot5^{570}. \end{align*}
Simplifying, we get
\begin{align*} a+2\min(a,b) &= 60\\ b+2\max(a,b) &= 570. \end{align*}
Subtracting the second equation from twice the first gives $-a+b = 210$, or $b = a+210$. Since $a\leq b$, we have $a\leq a+210$, which implies that $a\leq a+210$, which implies that $a\leq a+210$. This inequality is always true, so we must have equality, which gives $2\min(a,a+210) + a = 60$ and $\max(a,a+210) + b = 570$. Solving these equations, we find that $a = 30$ and $b = 240$. The number of (not necessarily distinct) prime factors in the prime factorization of $x$ is $3a = 90$, and the number of (not necessarily distinct) prime factors in the prime factorization of $y$ is $3b = 720$. Therefore, the value of $3m+2n$ is $3(90) + 2(720) = 1950$</answer>
